Let $\R$ be the real number line with the usual (Euclidean) topology.
Let $A \subseteq \R$ be defined as:
{{begin-eqn}}
{{eqn | l = A
      | o = :=
      | r = \openint 0 1 \cup \openint 1 2
      | c = {{Defof|Union of Adjacent Open Intervals}}
}}
{{eqn | o =
      | ro= \cup
      | r = \set 3
      | c = {{Defof|Singleton}}
}}
{{eqn | o =
      | ro= \cup
      | r = \paren {\Q \cap \openint 4 5}
      | c = Rational Numbers from $4$ to $5$ (not inclusive)
}}
{{end-eqn}}
The complement of $A$ in $\R$ is given by:
{{begin-eqn}}
{{eqn | l = A'
      | r = \hointl \gets 0
      | c = {{Defof|Unbounded Closed Real Interval}}
}}
{{eqn | o =
      | ro= \cup
      | r = \set 1
      | c = {{Defof|Singleton}}
}}
{{eqn | o =
      | ro= \cup
      | r = \hointr 2 3
      | c = {{Defof|Half-Open Real Interval}}
}}
{{eqn | o =
      | ro= \cup
      | r = \hointl 3 4
      | c = ... adjacent to Half-Open Real Interval
}}
{{eqn | o =
      | ro= \cup
      | r = \paren {\paren {\R \setminus \Q} \cap \closedint 4 5}
      | c = Irrational Numbers from $4$ to $5$
}}
{{eqn | o =
      | ro= \cup
      | r = \hointr 5 \to
      | c = {{Defof|Unbounded Closed Real Interval}}
}}
{{end-eqn}}
